{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17004"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17004"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.12,0.18,0.53,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68200"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53657"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11135"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68200"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn girl is examined shortly after birth. The pregnancy was complicated by intrauterine growth restriction noted on ultrasound scans. She was delivered at 38 weeks gestation with a birth weight of 1.9 kg. She has no significant family history and her parent\u0027s antenatal screening was declined. On examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 150/min, blood pressure 65/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 65/min, SpO2 89% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. She has a small jaw, low-set ears, clenched fists with overlapping fingers, and prominent calcanei (rocker-bottom feet). A loud systolic murmur is heard on cardiac examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["DiGeorge syndrome","Down syndrome","Patau syndrome","Edwards syndrome","Turner syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis newborn presents with multiple congenital anomalies characteristic of Edwards syndrome (trisomy 18). The key features include intrauterine growth restriction, characteristic facial features (micrognathia, low-set ears), clenched fists with overlapping fingers, and rocker-bottom feet. Congenital heart defects are present in up to 90% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEdwards syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the presence of an extra chromosome 18 and occurs in approximately 1 in 5,000 live births. Most cases (\u0026gt;95%) result from nondisjunction during meiosis. The prognosis is poor, with median survival of 5-15 days, though about 5-10% of children survive beyond the first year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDown syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (trisomy 21) typically presents with hypotonia, upslanting palpebral fissures, and a flat facial profile. While congenital heart defects are common, the characteristic features described in this case (particularly the rocker-bottom feet and clenched fists) are not typical of Down syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatau syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (trisomy 13) often presents with holoprosencephaly, microphthalmia, cleft lip/palate, and polydactyly, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETurner syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (45,X) affects only females and typically presents with lymphedema at birth, webbed neck, and coarctation of the aorta. The facial and limb features described are not consistent with Turner syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiGeorge syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (22q11.2 deletion) typically presents with cardiac defects, hypocalcemia, and thymic hypoplasia. The characteristic facial and limb features described in this case are not typical of DiGeorge syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Edwards syndrome (trisomy 18) typically presents with characteristic features including low-set ears, micrognathia, clenched fists, and rocker-bottom feet.","Most cases of Edwards syndrome are diagnosed prenatally through genetic screening.","The prognosis of Edwards syndrome is poor, with median survival of 5-15 days."],"references":["Balasundaram P, Avulakunta ID. Edwards Syndrome. 2023 Mar 20. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 34033359."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53657"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17004"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53657"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:39:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:40:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9694"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68200"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"e